stimulus:
Welcome to our study!


Our experiment is about decision making. You will choose and rate different food items, such as these:

This is a multi-part study.

In the first part you will rate 24 food items twice.


In the second part (longest) you will make repeated choices and judgements concerning the food items.


In the third and final part, you will rate the items again and answer few short questionnaires.

In the first part of the task you will use the mouse to rate food items on 2 scales


When you see the heart cue you will rate food items in terms of how much like them/would like to eat them right now. You will rate them on a continuous scale from left (strong dislike) to right (strong liking). Before submitting your rating, try imagining how the item tastes and how much you desire it.

When you see the size cue, you will rate the same food items in terms of their size. The scale goes from left (tiny) to right (very large). You should assess picture size relative to the white background. Remember: rate the size of the picture, not the size of the item in real life.



Notice: by starting the rating you agree that your sumbission might be rejected at an early stage and the experiment might end, if your size ratings are not at least modestly related to objective sizes, or if you repeat the same value ratings too many times. If you don't agree, please exit by closing the browser window.

Using the mouse, rate the likeness of the food items (how much you like them/would like to eat them right now). Far right-end of the scale indicates an item you like a lot. Far left-end indicates an item you dislike a lot. Think about each answer.
  • Try not to give identical rating to different items.
  • Use the whole scale, and not just the extremes
End of the first rating

Using the mouse, rate the size of the food items relative to the white background. Right-end of the scale indicates a very large item, which covers a large portion of the white rectangle. Left-end indicates a very tiny item which covers a tiny portion of the white rectangle.

Remember: everything that is not the white background also contributes to item size (e.g. packing, plates, ect.)

Please keep in mind that if the accuracy of ratings do not allign well with actual sizes, the experiment will end. As a result it will be consider incomplete and therefore no payment would be made. Good luck!

This is not a memory test - you don't need to be consistent with your previous ratings. Just as before, try to make accurate judgements.

SHORT BREAK

Please wait 5 seconds to continue

In the main part of the study, you will be choosing between 2 items. When it's time to choose, this symbol will appear:



Below, a cue will signify the type of choice:

Heart cue means you should choose the item you prefer more.

Size cue means you should choose the larger item.


When you click, a green square will appear around the item you chose.

Your choices should be both fast and accurate.

You will have 4 seconds to make each choice, which should be enough consider the options and click on one of the items.

Additionally, on some choice trials you will see the no-choice cue:



This cue means you can't make any choice. You can examine the items, but can't click on any of them. Just wait patiently for the cue to dissapear.

After each choice the items will remain on the screen and you will see this symbol:



This means you should rate the magnitude of the difference between the items using a scale:

Heart cue means you should rate how much you prefer one of the items over the other. Moving the scale indicator to the left means you prefer the left one; moving it to the right - right one. The more you prefer one of them, the more towards that side you should move the scale indicator.

Size cue means you should rate how much larger is one of the items over the other. Moving the scale indicator to the left means you think the left is larger; moving it to the right - right one. The greater the difference in size, the more towards that side you should move the scale indicator.

The main part of the experiment will consist of 3 blocks. Each block consists of 66 decisions and judgements. You will have time for a short break between blocks.


Do your best to respond within the time limit.
